  "prompt": "What is the difference between adding and committing in Git?",
  "response": "In Git, \"adding\" and \"committing\" are two distinct but related steps in the version control workflow.\n\n### Adding (`git add`)\n- **Purpose**: The `git add` command is used to add changes in your working directory to the staging area (also known as the index). \n- **Functionality**: When you modify files in your repository, those changes are not automatically included in the next commit. You need to specify which changes you want to include by using `git add`. This can be done for individual files, multiple files, or even for all changes in the directory.\n- **Example**: \n  - To stage a single file: `git add filename.txt`\n  - To stage all changes: `git add .`\n\n### Committing (`git commit`)\n- **Purpose**: The `git commit` command is used to create a snapshot of the changes you have added to the staging area. It permanently records those changes in the repository's history.\n- **Functionality**: When you commit changes, you also provide a descriptive message that explains what changes were made and why. This message is important for tracking the history of the project.\n- **Example**:\n  - To commit staged changes with a message: `git commit -m \"Your commit message\"`\n\n### Summary\n- **`git add`** stages changes for the next commit.\n- **`git commit`** creates a new commit with all the changes that were staged.\n\nIn a typical workflow, you would modify files, use `git add` to stage those changes, and then use `git commit` to permanently save them in the repository history.",
